File Operations

Navigation

pwd: Print working directory.
ls: List directory contents (-l for long format, -a for all files).
cd <directory>: Change directory.
cd: Go to home directory.
cd ..: Move up one directory.
File & Directory Manipulation

mkdir <directory_name>: Create a directory.
touch <file_name>: Create an empty file.
cp <source> <destination>: Copy files or directories (-r for recursive directory copy).
mv <source> <destination>: Move or rename files or directories.
rm <file_name>: Remove a file (-r for recursive directory removal, -i for interactive deletion).
Viewing & Editing

cat <file_name>: Display file contents.
less <file_name>: View a file page by page.
head <file_name>: Display the first 10 lines.
tail <file_name>: Display the last 10 lines.
nano <file_name> / vim <file_name> / emacs <file_name>: Open a file in a text editor.
Git Commands

Configuration

git config --global user.name "Your Name": Set your name.
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com": Set your email.
Repository Setup

git init: Initialize a new repository.
git clone <repository_url>: Clone a remote repository.
Making Changes

git add <file>: Stage a file.
git add .: Stage all changes.
git commit -m "Commit message": Commit changes.
git status: Check the status of changes.
git diff: View changes.
Branches

git branch: List branches.
git branch <branch_name>: Create a branch.
git checkout <branch_name>: Switch branches.
git merge <branch_name>: Merge a branch.
Remotes

git remote add origin <repository_url>: Add a remote.
git push -u origin <branch_name>: Push changes.
git pull origin <branch_name>: Pull changes.
Undoing Changes

git checkout -- <file>: Discard changes in a file.
git reset HEAD <file>: Unstage a file.
git revert <commit_hash>: Revert a commit.
GitHub Commands (web/CLI)

Repository

Create a new repository on GitHub.com.
Fork a repository on GitHub.com.
Collaboration

Create a pull request on GitHub.com.
Manage issues on GitHub.com.
Important Notes

.gitignore: Create a .gitignore file to exclude files from tracking.
git log: View commit history.
git help <command>: Get help with a Git command.
Case-sensitivity: Commands and filenames are case-sensitive.
Wildcards: Use * and ? for pattern matching.
Caution with rm -rf: It permanently deletes files/directories.
